h brubeck concert and new dukakis comment; picks up 10th graf pvs bgng, `james c.'</note>
the nation's governors appealed to the white house sunday for relief from 163 federal rules and regulations, and heard a former governor call for a constitutional convention to restore states' rights
new hampshire gov. john h. sununu, opening the national governors' association's winter meeting, said that the time has come to press for a new division of authority between the states and washington
there has been an erosion of the fundamental balance struck 200 years ago in philadelphia,'' sununu, the nga chairman, said at a news conference before gaveling the first plenary session to order
president reagan, at a black-tie dinner for the governors sunday night, told the governors he envied the balanced-budget requirements and line-item vetoes that many of them possess. ``not one of you would put up with the mess that we have here in washington at budget time,'' the president said
he also said he did not want to tie his successor's hands, but expressed hope the next president would continue his tradition of inviting the governors to the white house for dinner each year
reagan exchanged toasts with sununu, who said to reagan, ``from all of us to one of us: you did it your way. you did it well. god speed.''
the president planned to hold a working meeting with the governors monday to hear their concerns about regulations and other matters
the dave brubeck quartet brought the reagans and their guests to their feet with a concert that included w.c. handy's ``st. louis blues,'' duke ellington's ``take the a train'' and brubeck's own signature piece, ``take five.'' brubeck was joined by his longtime clarinet player bill smith, randy jones on drums and brubeck's son, chris, on bass guitar and slide trombone
reagan paid tribute to the jazz great, saying, ``it is magic. i know it's sort of a cliche, but they not only don't write 'em that way anymore, there aren't many around who play 'em anymore.''
forty-four governors were on hand for the affair, including presidential hopeful michael dukakis of massachusetts, who quipped about his visit to the white house, ``we've been looking it over, checking it out. i've never lived over the store before.''
dukakis planned to depart the governors' meeting monday to resume campaigning in south dakota and minnesota, which hold a primary and caucus respectively feb. 23
james c. miller iii, director of the office of management and budget, told the governors the reagan administration has carried out nearly 50 of 80 recommendations the nga made 16 months ago to reduce red tape and administrative burdens on state and local governments
eyeing the new stack of 163 recommendations, miller said, ``there's a lot more out there that needs to be done. it's hard to do.'' but he added, ``there is no question that our federal system of shared power between the federal and state governments ... is healthier today than it has been in years.''
the governors heard just the opposite from former georgia gov. george busbee, who warned, ``we are about one recession away from a complete breakdown of domestic government in this country.''
busbee, an atlanta lawyer who governed georgia from 1975 to 1983, urged the governors to press for a constitutional convention ``to break the gridlock, sift through the blue smoke and mirrors and restore a sense of order and accountability in american government.''
the federal government is raiding state and local revenue sources and dumping unfunded mandates on the states, busbee said, and most of the presidential candidates are talking of new federal initiatives in such areas of traditional state control as education, welfare, economic development and criminal justice
begging congress or the administration to pay attention to federalism is, in my opinion, a waste of time,'' said busbee, a democrat. ``governors and legislators are not treated much differently from the `national association of ball peen hammer producers' _ except that (they) have a pac (political action committee) and you don't.''
even as miller and sununu exchanged thick lists of regulatory reforms _ past, present and yet to come _ north dakota gov. george a. sinner was asking the omb chief if he could stop a controversial effort to force state guananteed student loan agencies to send a quarter-billion dollars of their reserves back to washington
but miller said that was part of the bipartisan deficit-reduction measures congress and the administration hammered out late last year, and ``i don't think it's likely to be changed.''
arkansas gov. bill clinton said he thought the reagan administration was ``genuinely trying,'' but there are still too many ``conflicting regulations that drive us nuts,'' especially in health and welfare
it took us two years to get rejected for a waiver on welfare reform,' clinton complained
reagan and the governors tried and failed to engineer a grand swap of federal and state responsibilities in 1982, including a complete federal takover of the medicaid program. reagan's so-called ``new federalism'' foundered as the administration tried to inflict simultaneous budget cuts on the programs
the theme of the governor's winter meeting, ``restoring the balance: state leadership for america's future,'' is hardly new. the governor's 1980 meeting centered on ``restoring balance to the federal system.''
but virginia gov. gerald l. baliles said that does not gainsay the importance of the new federalism initiative. ``federalism is a process. ...'' he said. ``it's a journey rather than a destination.''
the winter meeting runs through tuesday. sununu said he hopes the governors will decide by their meeting this summer on what strategies to pursue on regulatory reform, any changes in federal laws and the possibility of a constitutional convention
the governors' list of 163 regulatory reforms includes a raft of proposals for standardizing eligibility rules for food stamps and aid to families with dependent children, and easing up on strictures for running job training, education and health programs. with reagan hoping to free all american hostages before end of his term. pickup 12th graf pvs ``hezbollah is...''; edits thereafter to tighten</note>
iranian-backed hezbollah extremists shot at shiite militiamen searching a southeastern village for a kidnapped u.s. marine on sunday and declared support for his abductors
the members of justice minister nabih berri's mainstream shiite amal militia fired back with rocket-propelled grenades during the half-hour clash in ein el-tineh but no injuries were reported, a police spokesman said
hezbollah gunners later pounded israel's self-designated security zone in south lebanon with mortars, said the spokesman, who spoke on condition of anonymity according to regulations
he said israel retaliated by shelling 13 southern shiite villages for three hours. four civilians were wounded, police said
a hezbollah leader said he believed the u.s. marine, lt. col. william r. higgins, had been smuggled out of south lebanon
we declare solidarity with, and full support for, the strugglers against america who confront the plots of the great satan,'' said a statement from hezbollah, or party of god. ``the demands of the organization of the oppressed on earth are just.''
the organization of the oppressed on earth on friday claimed responsibility for higgins' kidnapping, charging he was a cia spy. u.s. and u.n. officials denied the charge
the group early monday called on berri to order his amal militia to stop house raids and arrests in connection with higgins' abduction
the pretention that he is defending the u.n. peacekeeping forces in south lebanon is not a viable excuse for rescuing an american espionage agent,'' the group said in a typewritten statement delivered to the independent beirut newspaper an-nahar just after midnight
we are lying in wait for any other suspicious american,'' the arabic language statement said
higgins, a decorated vietnam veteran and a one-time military assistant to former u.s. defense secretary caspar weinberger, heads a 76-man observer group attached to a u.n. peacekeeping force in south lebanon. he was kidnapped on wednesday near the ancient port city of tyre
in washington, president reagan said sunday night that ``we're doing everything we can and exploring every avenue'' to free higgins
asked if he hoped to get all american hostages freed from lebanon before he leaves office next january, the president said, ``i'd like that better than anything else.''
it is such a terrible situation and you're afraid you'll do something that will harm them (the hostages). we don't know who they (the captors) are or where they are,'' reagan told reporters during a reception at the white house for the national governors' association
hezbollah is believed to be the umbrella organization for pro-iranian groups holding foreign hostages in lebanon
ein el-tineh, a hezbollah stronghold, is 31 miles east of tyre, where hezbollah claims amal has arrested more than 150 of its members in connection with higgins' abduction. amal spokesmen say only 40 fundamentalists have been detained
the abduction prompted the u.n.'s interim forces in lebanon to withdraw 20 observers from higgins' unit to its headquarters in naqoura, near the israel-lebanon border, according to timor goksel, spokesman for the unifil
goksel said the observers were withdrawn both for security concerns and to protest higgins' abduction. the rest of the observer group remained sunday in positions overlooking beirut's green line, which divides the city into moslem and christian sectors, he said
goksel declined to comment on reports that u.n. troops had abandoned checkpoints around tyre
ten unifil troops were withdrawn thursday to naqoura from an area close to an amal checkpoint on the qassmieh highway bridge north of the city. but unifil troops did not withdraw from any of their own checkpoints south and east of tyre
unifil units and amal militiamen, aided by helicopters and dogs, continued to search for higgins sunday in olive and citrus groves and cave-lined valleys southeast of tyre
berri has called higgins' abduction a threat to the security of the predominantly shiite population of south lebanon. he said amal was bent on defending the u.n. peacekeeping force irrespective of the nationality of its officers
sheik abdul-karim obeid, a hezbollah leader in south lebanon, was quoted by beirut radio stations sunday as saying he believes the kidnappers have managed to smuggle higgins out of the south
obeid told warshippers at a mosque in the southern village of jibsheet that higgins was in charge of unifil's ``spying operations.''
as a condition of higgins' release, the oppressed on earth has demanded that israel withdraw from the security zone it carved out in south lebanon when the bulk of its occupation army withdrew from lebanon in 1985, ending a three-year invasion
it also demanded the release of lebanese and palestinian inmates held at the khiam detention camp in the security zone and in israeli jails
an estimated 300 detainees are believed held at khiam, run by militiamen of the israeli-backed south lebanon army
higgins was the third u.n. official abducted in south lebanon in three weeks
jan stening, 44, of sweden and willian jorgensen, 58, of norway, both employees of the u.n. relief and works agency that cares for palestinian refugees, were kidnapped feb. 5 near sidon, 25 miles north of tyre
there are 22 other foreigners missing in lebanon. they are eight americans, four frenchmen, three britons, two west germans, an italian, an indian and two unidentified men
the longest held is american terry anderson, chief middle east correspondent for the associated press. he was kidnapped march 16, 1985. sources ... of lublin.'</note>
authorities on sunday began freeing detained solidarity activists who had been stopped from attending a weekend meeting of the outlawed trade union
in southeastern poland, meanwhile, eight farmers protesting higher prices were arrested
police in the provincial city of rzeszow detained the farmers during a march by 150 people chanting: ``we want meat. we want bread.'' the march followed a national gathering of the banned farmers' union, rural solidarity
earlier at a mass in rzeszow attended by 2,000 people, local bishop ignacy tokarczuk sharply criticized the government's treatment of peasant farmers
the countryside should be united and only then it will win its demands,'' he said
the farmers' meeting coincided with the seventh anniversity of the government's 1981 agreement to recognize rural solidarity as a bargaining agent for farmers. the union later was declared illegal following the imposition of martial law
on sunday, authorities began to free members of the solidarity free trade union's national executive commission jailed over the weekend just before a planned meeting called in gdansk by solidarity chairman lech walesa
at least seven of the commission's 10 members and the union's national spokesman, janusz onyszkiewicz, were taken into custody friday and saturday
opposition sources said a small group of solidarity activists managed to meet anyway, and that a statement would be issued later
zbigniew bujak, former underground chief of the union and the warsaw-region representative on the commission, was freed sunday morning from a downtown warsaw police station, said ludwika wujec, a warsaw solidarity activist
union sources said others released later in the day were: onyszkiewicz, wladyslaw frasyniuk of wroclaw, antoni stawikowski of torun, antoni tokarczuk of bydgoszcz and stanislaw weglarz of lublin
there was no confirmation of the release of stefan jurczak, representative for the krakow region, and bogdan lis of gdansk, but they were also expected to be freed
in a sermon sunday in gdansk's st. brygida's church, the rev. henryk jankowski spoke angrily about the detentions
man's right to freedom and his freedom of thought are trampled,'' said jankowski, an adviser to walesa. ``this is an act of lawlessness that does moral harm to the nation.''
