paramount pictures and the disney co. are running neck and neck as the two giant film companies continue their battle for box office supremacy
for the past two years, paramount has been the unqualified leader among major distributors, scoring with such blockbusters as ``top gun,'' ``crocodile dundee'' and ``beverly hills cop ii.''
paramount's share of the domestic film market was 20 percent in 1987, according to daily variety financial expert art murphy. runners-up were buena vista, the disney distributing company, with 14 percent, and warner bros. with 13
in the first two weeks of 1988, buena vista took the lead on the strength of the smash hits ``three men and a baby'' and ``good morning vietnam'' _ 26 percent to paramount's 17. it was a happy triumph for disney chairman michael eisner and jeff katzenberg, disney's film production chief; both had previously worked for paramount
but no matter who takes the box-office crown, everybody wins in 1988
movie booms last at least 2{ years; the longest has been 3{,'' murphy said. ``this boom has lasted a year and a half, and i see no slowdown.''
the year has opened strongly, with a record take of $100 million in january. the period from jan. 1 to memorial day is traditionally the slowest period of the movie year, contributing 20 percent of annual ticket stales, compared to 40 percent for the three summer months
what wonders will theaters offer in the first five months of 1988? the mixture, as before, has a heavy accent on comedy
john hughes invades the yuppie world with ``she's having a baby,'' starring kevin bacon and elizabeth mcgovern. ann-margret falls for her daughter's boyfriend, c. thomas howell, in ``a tiger's tale.'' joe piscopo and treat williams play it for laughs as cops in ``dead heat.''
neil simon returns with the second of his autobiographical trilogy, ``biloxi blues,'' with matthew broderick and directed by mike nichols. george roy hill (``the sting'') is back with ``funny farm,'' in which new yorkers chevy chase and madolyn smith try the rural life. richard pryor as an engineer moves his family from new jersey to idaho in ``moving.''
the ageless george burns changes brains with his grandson in ``18 again,'' which might bring to mind ``like father like son.''
the gods must be crazy ii'' follow the adventures of the engaging african bushman, n!xau. richard dreyfuss continues his roll as an actor who impersonates a central american dictator in ``moon over parador.''
front page'' is replayed in tv land with kathleen turner, burt reynolds and christopher reeve in ``switching channels.'' sally field and tom hanks star as a pair of stand-up comics in ``punchline.''
those raucous rookies return in ``police academy 5: assignment miami beach,'' this time without steve gutenberg
distributors always release a heavy load of dramas in the early part of the year, when competition for the youth market is at a minimum. the most anticipated film is ``the unbearable lightness of being,'' based on the modern classic novel by milan kundera. it is the first movie by philip kaufman since ``the right stuff.''
also long-awaited is robert redford's first film as a director since ``ordinary people'' _ ``the milangro beanfield war,'' about a new mexico native who fights developers
after sinking with ``pirates,'' roman polanski goes back to the mystery-adventure genre with ``frantic,'' starring harrison ford as a surgeon whose wife disappears. kelly mcgillis and jeff daniels appear in a postwar drama about the smuggling of nazi criminals into the united states, ``house on carroll street.'' edward james olmos (``miami vice'') and lou diamond phillips (``la bamba'') appear in ``stand and deliver,'' about a dedicated teacher in east l.a
roger vadim has modernized his 1957 film ``and god created women'' with rebecca demornay in the role that helped make brigitte bardot famous. blake edwards presents an imaginary teaming of tom mix (bruce willis) and wyatt earp (james garner) to solve a murder mystery in ``sunset.''
sidney poitier returns to the screen as an fbi agent in a pair of films: ``shoot to kill,'' a crime chase with tom beringer; and ``little nikita,'' with river phoenix as son of soviet spies
alan alda breaks his absence from films as director-writer-star with ann-margret in ``a new life,'' about a divorced pair seeking new lives
in ``bright lights, big city,'' michael j. fox abandons his sunshiny image to play a cocaine-sniffing yuppie in the manhattan fast lane. kelly mcgillis and john shea are pioneering israelis in ``dreamers.'' don johnson takes a shot at the big screen in ``sweet hearts dance,'' a romantic drama co-starring susan sarandon
the new year will bring plenty of action, too. comic jay leno makes his film debut as a detroit cop teaming with a tokyo detective (pat morita) in ``collision course.'' gene hackman is a pilot downed in vietnam and danny glover is his rescuer in ``bat 21.'' the vietnam trend continues with ``off limits,'' in which willem dafoe and gregory hines investigate murders of vietnamese prostitues
academy award winners william hurt and timothy hutton combine for a world war ii thriller, ``destiny.'' sean penn appears in two films: ``judgment in berlin,'' as one of three east berliners escaping in an airplane; and in ``colors'' as a police partner with robert duvall battling los angeles gangs
the macho men are also back: charles bronson investigates mormon cult murders in ``messenger of death''; scott glenn is a cop who becomes an al capone henchman in ``verne miller.''
there's an ample supply of horror and teen films, as well as some that are hard to classify: ``eat the rich,'' ``killer klowns (from outer space),'' ``hazing in hell'' and ``zombie cop.''
austrian president kurt waldheim was never a soviet agent, according to his former under-secretary at the united nations, arkady shevchenko, a soviet defector who lives in the united states, a london newspaper reported sunday
in light of allegations surrounding waldheim's service in the german army during world war ii, there has been speculation in the western press that the soviets might have held incriminating documents against him and threatened to use them if he did not comply with their policies when he was u.n. secretary-general from 1972 to 1982
the sunday telegraph said it was told by shevchenko in washington recently that the speculation is unfounded
shevchenko was reported as saying the soviet foreign ministry had other candidates in mind when waldheim's name first came up for the u.n. post
it was only when we saw he was likely to emerge as clear favorite that we gave him our backing and actually put him up for the job,'' shevchenko said
shevchenko defected from his u.n. post in 1978. before taking his post at the united nations he was secretary in moscow to andrei gromyko, then soviet foreign minister
the defector said he saw gromyko's personal file on waldheim
it mentioned that he had fought on our russian front and had been wounded there. but there was absolutely no reference to any war crimes,'' shevchenko was quoted as saying
shevchenko was further quoted as saying that senior officials of the soviet kgb secret police in charge of soviet citizens in new york, complained of their inability to influence waldheim in getting more soviets appointed to his staff and of their being frozen out of his inner circle
an international commission has investigated allegations waldheim was involved in german atrocities in the balkans in world war ii while serving in the german army. waldheim has repeatedly denied the allegations and has rejected calls that he step down as president
the historians' commission, formed by the austrian government, concluded this month that waldheim was ``in close proximity'' to some nazi atrocities in the balkans, knew they were going on and made no attempt to prevent them. it also said waldheim concealed his wartime past and tried to make it seem harmless once he could no longer hide it
the commmission's report did not support allegations waldheim committed atrocities. but it left open the question of whether he was guilty of any crime
