william claiborne ``red'' hayes jr., the nasa official who greeted astronaut john glenn after his history-making flight in 1962, died saturday. he was 63
hayes, who spent 27 years with the national aeronautics and space administration, directed the at-sea recovery efforts that plucked astronauts from the ocean after their space capsules had returned to earth
when glenn was brought aboard the navy aircraft carrier randolph after america's first manned orbital flight, hayes was the first to greet him and shake his hand
hayes, a norfolk native, joined the national advisory committee on aeronautics in 1952 and was there when nasa was organized a few years later
from 1952 to 1961, he was assigned to nasa's langley research center where he worked with wind-tunnel research
in 1961 he was transferred to the manned spacecraft center in houston, texas, and was given charge of the recovery operations section. hayes directed the recovery of astronauts glenn, scott carpenter, walter schirra and gus grissom
the rescues were not without mishaps. grissom had to be rescued after his capsule sank, and carpenter's capsule seemed to disappear after its re-entry into the atmosphere and it took an hour to locate it. when carpenter was finally airlifted to the carrier intrepid, hayes again was first in line to shake his hand
in 1969, hayes became director of the advanced aerospace projects office at nasa-langley, and in 1971 he was named executive assistant for planning in the office of the director for center development and external affairs at langley
a year later, he was named director of the manned space technology office at nasa headquarters in washington, d.c., where he was responsible for the development of advanced technology requirements for the space shuttle, space stations, planetary spacecraft and other projects
hayes retired in 1979
he is survived by a wife, mildred mcwilliams hayes; a son; and a daughter. funeral services were scheduled for monday in purcellville. order</head> update with comment from union official, who said firefighters expected to return to work. picks up 5th graf pvs, `the city...'.</note>
much of the city fire department's day shift called in sick saturday, apparently because of a dispute with city officials over the equipping of new emergency units, a city spokeswoman said
the city late saturday afternoon persuaded superior court judge john e. orton iii to issue a temporary restraining order requiring the firefighters to return to work sunday, said barbara cottam, spokeswoman for mayor joseph r. paolino jr. it is illegal for municipal employees to strike in rhode island
leo miller, president of providence firefighters local 799, said he expected the firefighters to return to work sunday. city officials had vowed to return to orton and seek contempt citations if the job action continued, ms. cottam said
that's what the city tells you,'' was all miller would say when asked if the sickout was organized as part of a contract dispute. ``what i'm going to say is that we thought we had a contract with them but they have reneged.''
neither ms. cottam nor miller had figures on the number of firefighters who called in sick. the city covered the shifts of the absent workers by holding the friday night shift over, ms. cottam said
the city, in a contract reached last year with the firefighters' union, agreed to increase the number of rescue units in the department from three to five
ms. cottam said the union is insisting that the two new units, like the existing ones, be equipped with advanced life-support equipment
that was never discussed or agreed to and it is not necessary,'' ms. cottam said. ``the need is not there.''
she also said the department does not have enough rescue workers with the special training required for the advanced life-support systems to staff five units. hospital confirmation</note>
two women were killed and two wounded saturday night after they were herded into an apartment bedroom, bound and shot execution-style in an apparent drug related incident, police and television reports said
officers found one woman dead at the apartment in the northwest section of the nation's capital and a second woman was pronounced dead at the washington hospital center, said police capt. william ritchie. he said police were seeking four suspects
the washington hospital center was treating a third victim in its intensive care unit, a spokeswoman, who refused to be identified, said. the fourth woman, who was shot in the arm, was treated at howard university hospital and released, said administrator deborah shields
reporters on the scene for wrc-tv and wttg-tv said police entered the apartment to find one woman dead of a gunshot wound to the head and two others severely wounded. four small children, some of them in diapers, were huddled around
the woman shot in the arm managed to crawl to a neighbor's apartment and called for help, the tv reports said. police said they received the call at 7:21 p.m
the television reports said the women were described by the police as in their early 20s and as possibly jamaican
on jan. 22, police in nearby prince georges county, md., found four men and one woman shot dead in what was also described as a drug-related slaying. police have issued arrest warrants in that case for three jamaican men from brooklyn, n.y
foreign minister eduard a. shevardnadze said his government wants to play ``a more active role'' in the search for an arab-israeli settlement as he opened talks sunday with secretary of state george p. shultz
the issue of soviet participation is among key items on shultz' agenda for his two days of talks here
shultz on saturday said the soviets should ``face up'' to their human rights problems and establish relations with israel if they intend to take part in the talks he will try to set up when he goes to the middle east next week
but shevardnadze, chatting with a reporter while waiting for shultz at the soviet foreign ministry's elegant guest house in central moscow, said his government already was playing a ``constructive role'' in the region
we want to play a more active role also in the negotiations,'' he said
israeli prime minister yitzhak shamir has resisted soviet participation in the search for a middle east settlement
the soviets have supported jordan and egypt in calling for an international conference to serve as a framework for arab-israeli negotiations. shamir is cool to the idea, and appears to have support from shultz
shultz' talks here are intended to prepare for the next superpower summit meeting between president reagan and soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev. it is to be held in moscow, likely by mid-summer, but the date has not been set
a date could be set before shultz departs
shultz flew in from helsinki, finland, where on saturday he met with reporters to discuss soviet policy on human rights and regional problems
the presence of soviet troops in afghanistan and u.s. support for afghan rebels is also on the agenda. gorbachev announced earlier this month that a soviet pullout could begin may 15 and be completed within 10 months if u.n.-sponsored negotiations in geneva next month can put together a formal agreement by march 15
talks between soviet and u.s. officials traditionally cover four areas _ arms control, human rights, matters of bilateral interest and regional conflicts. rescheduled for today, airline employees to go to work. picks up 8th graf, `the 12:01...'</note>
talks between representatives of pan am corp. and 4,500 teamsters workers broke up sunday after continuing six hours past a 12:01 a.m. strike deadline, and union officials said employees would return to work sunday
the negotiations, aimed at resolving a dispute over pan am's demands for wage cuts and work-rule changes, were scheduled to resume sunday afternoon, said alex calder, a spokesman for the teamsters' airlines division
calder refused to discuss the status of the talks, saying the union leadership is hesitant to read too much into them
earlier sunday, william genoese, director of the airline division of teamsters local 732, announced that the workers had overwhelmingly authorized a strike, although he refused to release figures on the vote
these people are fed up,'' he said of the workers. the teamsters union contends it has made sufficient concessions to aid the financially ailing airline
pan am said that in case of a strike, it would maintain service by using replacement workers for the union members, who are employed as reservation clerks, customer service agents and in various clerical positions
pan am spokeswoman pamela hanlon said talks resumed at 10:30 p.m. saturday in new york at the request of a federal mediator
genoese said that despite the resumption of talks, there was a good chance of a strike. ``they waited too long. they dragged their feet,'' he said
the 12:01 a.m. deadline marked the end of a 30-day cooling-off period mandated by the government
the transport workers union voted friday not to support a teamsters' strike, and the financially ailing airline's pilots, flight attendants and flight engineers unions were not expected to back a strike
another pan am spokesman, jeff kriendler, said: ``the company is prepared to negotiate and wants a settlement. but if there is a strike we're fully prepared to operate.''
replacement workers, including management employees, were trained and ready to replace strikers, kriendler said
genoese said thursday that there was enough support for local 732 among other teamsters locals to cut off the airline's supplies of fuel, laundry and liquor around the world
the union represents workers at airports in boston, detroit, chicago, seattle, san francisco, san diego, los angeles, hawaii, houston, washington, new york and the florida cities of tampa, orlando and miami
about 2,300 of the workers are employed in new york and another 1,300 are in miami, goenese said
china reaped a $1 billion bonanza from weapons sales to iran last year, but is not expected to block an iranian arms embargo the united states is seeking in the united nations security council, u.s. officials said
the most recent u.s. intelligence estimates show that iran received up to 65 percent of its armaments from china last year, said the officials, speaking on condition of anonymity
american experts were quoted four months ago as saying chinese arms to iran were flowing at a rate of $1 billion a year, and the officials said that figure appears to have held up through the end of 1987
china also has sold huge amounts of weapons to iraq since the beginning of the iran-iraq war in 1980, but those sales slacked off last year, the officials said
there is still some question whether china is continuing to ship silkworm missiles to iran, according to the officials. these anti-ship missiles are the most notorious weapons in the iranian arsenal because they have been fired from shoreline batteries against international shipping in the persian gulf
the united states _ notably during a face-to-face confrontation by secretary of state george p. shultz in beijing last spring _ pleaded with china to stop the silkworm sales. for months, china denied the sales were taking place. then it acknowledged that iran may have been getting them indirectly through other countries and said it would try to stop that flow
this was construed as a face-saving way for china to say two things at the same time: they weren't selling silkworms to iran and that they were stopping them,'' an official said
also in iran's arsenal of chinese weapons are small arms, ammunition, machine guns and artillery, the officials said
the united states has protested the sales by ending a decade-long process of easing restrictions on the type of high-tech u.s. equipment china can buy. the decision will make it harder for china to buy computers and advanced electronics now reaching the market
according to one official, china has sold $7 billion in arms to iran and iraq since 1979, but congressional research service estimates indicate this figure might be inflated
in a report to congress last may, the service estimated that china's total arms sales to all third world countries totaled nearly $7.3 billion between 1979 and 1986. in the last four years of that period, china ranked fourth, behind the soviet union, the united states and france, in that order, in sales to third world countries
even with the discrepancy, ``there's no doubt that chinese sales to iran are very large,'' a congressional expert said
last july 20, the u.n. security council passed a resolution calling upon iran and iraq to end the war and said it would follow with a second resolution imposing an arms embargo on whichever country failed to heed the truce call
iraq has agreed to a cease-fire, but iran has not, so the united states and its allies on the u.n. body are now pressing for the arms embargo against tehran
shultz is expected to press the soviets, during talks in moscow this week, to agree to the second resolution
china, a permanent member of the security council, theoretically could veto an arms embargo resolution
an official specializing in chinese affairs said, however, the chinese are unlikely to exercise that right
china has always taken a passive role at the united nations,'' the official said. `` being influential at the u.n. goes against the chinese view that it should not seek to hegemony in world affairs, as it charges the united states and the soviet union always does.''
they are not going to favor the resolution _ it will hurt them too much financially _ but they probably won't block it,'' the official said
state officials have silenced a proposal by two units of the department of environmental protection for a morning ``quiet hour.''
employees in the water pollution and waste disposal units planned to initiate a ``quiet hour'' from 10 a.m. to noon. during that time employees wouldn't take calls or visitors without an appointment
supervisors said the department's office building in hartford was so noisy and crowded that employees needed the time to get work done
the building is a pit. we've got to do something to make it possible for people to do their work,'' said michael j. harder, assistant director of the department's water compliance unit
the proposal, however, was rejected. ``we're a public agency, and we have to remain open to the public,'' deputy dep commissioner john anderson said friday
two men were accused in a federal indictment of persuading more than 1,000 people to invest $12.6 million in recordings by celebrities, which were promoted as tax shelters
the recordings, which included a cooking lesson, sports instruction program and religious story, were performed by celebrities including tommy lasorda, vincent price, billy dee williams, pat boone, dale evans and shirley jones
none of the celebrities was accused of wrongdoing
according to the indictment unsealed friday, the programs were operated in 1981 and 1982 by entertainment marketing co. inc., which was based in hollywood and controlled by johnathan d'orio, 40, now of akron, ohio, and daniel f. schustack, 38, now of new york city
the indictment alleged the two bilked 1,150 investors out of more than $12.6 million by inflating the value of the audio tapes and promising huge tax credits
the internal revenue service disallowed the tax deductions and credits and assessed interest and substantial penalties against investors, katz said
d'orio was due in court in akron on monday, while schustack will be summoned to appear in court in los angeles, assistant u.s. attorny david katz said
the number of homeless people in boston rose more than 17 percent to about 3,400 in the last 15 months, and more women and children are living on boston's streets and in its shelters than ever before, according to preliminary results of a survey
ann maguire, director of boston's emergency shelter commission, said the new figures were complied from a homeless census taken early friday, when more than 100 volunteers counted homeless people in city streets and alleys
boston officials said no other city in the country does similar street counts. the first street census of the city's homeless, conducted in november 1986, found about 2,900 homeless people
of the approximately 3,400 counted friday, 20.4 percent were women, 10.5 percent children and adolescents and the rest men, maguire said saturday
a survey of 26 cities released by the u.s. conference of mayors in december found a 21 percent increase in the demand for emergency shelter, ranging from a 44 percent jump in kansas city to no change in louisville
the national survey found families with children accounting for one third of homeless in 1987
boston mayor raymond l. flynn is chairman of the mayors conference task force on hunger and homelessness. boston increases its number of shelter beds last year by 47 percent, maguire said
in a telephone interview saturday night, flynn called on other cities to conduct similar surveys to give the mayors conference a weapon during congressional budget deliberations
flynn said most members of congress ``believe the problem is basically confined to street people and don't realize the number of families and mentally ill. we need the data to impress that upon them.''
a sphinx small enough to fit in the palm of a hand was found in the tomb of a woman who died 2,000 years ago, one of a bounty of clues that may link two ancient civilizations, experts said sunday
the sphinx, only 1{ inches tall, was among 420 trinkets found dangling from a necklace found at the burial site, which dates back to 200 b.c. to 200 a.d., abdel-aziz soweileh, bahrain's antiquities supervisor, was quoted as saying in the newspaper akhbar al-khaleej
also found was a scarab, a beetle-shaped insignia, and a perfume vial. analysis of a skeleton in the grave indicated it belonged to a woman who was between the ages of 25 and 30 when she died
the newspaper quoted soweileh as saying that the items may link bahrain's ancient dilmun civilizations with pharaonic egypt. the sphinx typically has the body of a lion and head of a man
