anderson purdon, spokesman for british military authorities in west berlin, said the two ``were arrested saturday by berlin police in the british sector, and british authorities were informed about it.''
we informed the soviet embassy on the other side (in east berlin), and they were asked to send someone'' to pick up the two officers, he said
purdon would not comment on the alleged espionage activities or on why the officers weren't held by western authorities to face charges
the last reported aids patient in nigeria has died, a newspaper said sunday
mahammadu debas, a 42-year-old tailor from gambia, died friday, the vanguard newspaper said. his death brought to 12 the number of people who have died of acquired immune defiency syndrome in nigeria
the newspaper said debas was the last known aids victim in the country. nigeria reported its first aids case only eight months ago
debas' case became a controversy in nigeria when he was forcibly hospitalized by health authorities last august for five months. several doctors disputed the aids diagnosis
the man was released from a hospital last month at his own request
aids damages the body's immune system, leaving victims susceptible to infections and cancer. it is spread most often through sexual contact, needles or syringes shared by drug abusers, infected blood or blood products, and from pregnant women to their offspring
william rathje says archaeology is merely digging for ancient garbage, and he's updated the field of study by sifting through america's trash
for me, the past is yesterday, not 1,000 years ago. garbage is our past and garbage is our future,'' rathje, a professor of archaeology at the university of arizona, said in an interview thursday. ``it is a material artifact of our culture.''
information gathered from garbage helps reveal social trends and landfill hazards and augments commercial market research, said rathje, who grew up not far from this western chicago-area community
he and his students have picked through landfills here, in tucson, ariz., and in the san francisco area
two things his digs in tucson documented were a sharp increase in condom use and a rise in the number of people cutting fat off meat since health warnings about fatty meat were first published
although the diggings here have not been fully analyzed, they do show things such as newspapers making up 15 percent of the garbage by weight, compared to 9 percent in arizona and just 4 percent in san francisco
the work is not always unpleasant. rathje has found a diamond ring and about $15 a year in coins
but then there was the time he took his student crew to lunch at a crowded tucson eatery after a morning of digging through a landfill
within a half hour, the other customers had cleared out and the manager told him and his students when they left: ``don't hurry back.''
the object was to build a machine that could put a postage stamp on an envelope, and the entry from theta tau fraternity won handily _ taking 33 steps and involving dolls, eggs and a mousetrap
the not-so-simple contraption was an entry in the 1988 rube goldberg machine contest held saturday at purdue university
the annual competition, named for the cartoonist who specialized in drawing outlandishly complicated machines to perform simple tasks, drew six student teams
the machines had to successfully complete the task in under five minutes, using at least 25 steps, said mike barrett of highland, a student organizer
the theta tau machine's 33 steps included a miniature mailman that braved rain, snow and an attacking dog; fluid that was forced from a jar and into a tube spelling out ``david letterman;'' a doll of indiana university basketball coach bob knight that was dunked in a vat of green fluid; a sledge smashing an egg; a bubbling jar of antacid, and marbles and a mouse trap
we started planning at the start of the semester, and spent 400-500 hours working on details of the project,'' said steve zellers of indianapolis, a senior in mechanical engineering and spokesman for the winning team
for the device's grand finale, the envelope was shot into a mailbox, which interrupted an electric eye and tripped circuits that closed the mailbox door and flipped up a flag
a 16-year-old sentenced to two life terms for murdering his father, stepmother and 5-year-old sister will be in prison for at least two decades, prosecutors say 
eric poole of mcduffie county, who was sentenced friday, will not be eligible for parole for 20 years, according to district attorney dennis sanders
the victims, all shot repeatedly with a rifle, were discovered in the family's mobile home on feb. 7, 1987, two days after they were killed, sanders said
tony poole, 34, was ambushed as he walked in the front door, sanders said. janice poole, 31, was apparently shot while asleep and michele poole, 5, was shot six times, the prosecutor said
one or more industries apparently took advantage of a major fuel spill last month to dump cancer-causing industrial solvents into the ohio river, water quality experts say
they dumped dirty solvents because getting rid of them is expensive,'' said edgar berkey, executive vice president of the university of pittsburgh's center for hazardous materials research
what these misdirected and misguided industrial people dumped are chemicals and materials far more harmful, far more biologically active, than the diesel fuel,'' berkey said
an estimated 730,000 gallons of diesel oil poured from a ruptured ashland oil inc. tank into the monongahela river south of pittsburgh on jan. 2, then flowed into the ohio river. the fuel threatened drinking supplies for residents in pennsylvania, ohio, west virginia, kentucky, illinois and indiana
samples taken along a 15-mile stretch of the ohio river between wheeling and moundsville, w.va., the week of jan. 10 contained high concentrations of chloroform, methylene chloride, and 1,1,1-trichloroethane, according to peter tennant, water quality program manager for the ohio river valley sanitation commission in cincinnati
chloroform and methylene chloride are cancer-causing substances and can accumulate in the bodies of fish and other marine life. the third substance, 1,1,1-trichloroethane, also is toxic
it's not unusual to see those chemicals in that part of the river occasionally, but never at that high a concentration,'' tennant told the pittsburgh press in an article published sunday. ``offhand, i'd estimate those concentrations at about 10 times more than what we normally might see.''
at the time of the spill, we were getting calls from lots of industries up and down the river about where it was located,'' he said. ``we thought they were worried about their (water) intakes.''
at the levels found, chloroform and methylene chloride significantly exceed the federal cancer risk level criteria for rivers and streams, according to tennant
tennant said his commission has several aerial photographs taken during the fuel spill that seem to show discharges from the ohio side of the river below wheeling. the agency in the past has investigated reports of pollutant discharges at that site
tennant said the photographed discharges have not been identified and do not seem to be coming from any building or industrial facility. he declined to speculate about their origin, except to say they could be intermittently flowing from a drainage ditch or sewer
tennat said it's ``very doubtful'' that those responsible for discharging the chemicals will be identified
tennant said his commission will begin making its data available soon to a number of agencies and investigators. among those concerned is berkey, who is directing an independent study of the spill and its aftermath for ashland
gary bryant, epa's field office chief in wheeling, said ashland officials asked for test samples to be taken as the spill moved downriver to determine whether any other industry was adding to it
we were already doing testing of the spill to evaluate if someone was adding any spice to it,'' bryant said. ``in years past, absolutely we would see such dumping during a spill where someone would need to empty a bilge tank or whatever.''
there are 83 industrial discharge points along the 87 miles of the ohio river from pittsburgh to wheeling, according to the press. seventy of them are identified as containing low-level toxic components
senate democrats are trying once again to resolve the biggest hangover issue from 1987 _ putting brakes on the rising cost of congressional elections
negotiations began last week with republican opponents of the democratic campaign spending limit bill, which gop senators were able to derail last year with a gentlemanly filibuster
headed by senate republican leader bob dole of kansas, the republicans talked away 22 days of floor time and won a record seven votes to end the debate, with the democrats falling five votes short of the 60 needed to win the so-called cloture vote
the legislation, with 52 of the 100 senators as co-sponsors, made its 1988 reappearance on the floor last week, generating still more debate amid talk of compromise and warnings from senate majority leader robert byrd, d-w.va
byrd, a principal supporter of the bill, said that unless negotiators from both camps can work out a deal, he will get tough and keep the senate in session nights and weekends to break the impasse
if there is going to be a filibuster this time, it is not going to be a gentlemen's filibuster,'' byrd said, referring to last year's rather civilized daylight debate that never quite reached the gloves-off stage
i don't want to see a filibuster, but if it comes to that i suggest that senators cancel all evening engagements and be present as long as the senate is in session,'' he said. ``if it should develop into a full-blown overtime filibuster, senators should expect roll calls at any time.''
byrd's warnings were followed by both sides naming four members each to attempt to negotiate differences in what sen. thad cochran, r-miss., calls ``a power struggle between the two national parties for control of the senate.''
negotiators for the democrats are sens. david boren of okla., george mitchell of maine, carl levin of michigan and james exon of nebraska. the republicans are sens. mitch mcconnell of kentucky, bob packwood of oregon, ted stevens of alaska and rudy boschwitz of minnesota
they held their first meeting on thursday without any tangible result. an aide to one of the democrats, speaking on condition of anonymity, called it ``the reykjavik of campaign finance reform,'' a reference to the unproductive u.s-soviet summit of 1986
the negotiators are slated to meet again monday, but the aide said it appears one side or the other will have to make major concessions to produce a compromise
the democratic bill would set voluntary spending limits for general elections to the senate, ranging from $950,000 to $5.5 million, depending on a state's population. the average senate campaign cost $3 million in 1986, with the price soaring beyond $10 million in the big states
a candidate observing the limit would be able to get campaign money from the treasury if the opponent exceeded the limit or if an independent group spent large amounts of money against the candidate
republicans argue that because they generally are more successful in raising campaign funds, limits would hurt them more than democrats, especially as they continue to try to further their gains in the south
the gop critics also argue that the bill would further tilt the playing field against them because it would do nothing about an area where democrats generally are ahead
this is the so-called ``soft money,'' the term used to describe the aid given candidates by groups like labor unions, often in the form of manpower for phone banks and door-to-door canvassing
democrats so far have made no overt move to limit soft money, arguing that even if they agreed to tighten up on this form of campaign resources, the republicans would still insist on no spending limits
democrats outnumber republicans in the senate 54-46. two republicans are co-sponsoring the democratic bill, sens. robert stafford of vermont and john chafee of rhode island. sen. nancy landon kassebaum, r-kan., was the third republican supporting cloture last year. alabama democrats howell heflin and richard shelby voted against cloture
the republican caucus has made opposition to the bill a hard-line party issue. to win the battle, byrd's forces will have to break through the gop ranks, picking up the votes of a handful of republicans who are said to favor spending limits but who thus far have remained loyal to dole
last week the burner was turned up under four of them: sens. william roth of delaware, william cohen of maine, arlen specter of pennsylvania and larry pressler of south dakota
they were the targets of full-page ads in newspapers back home urging them to ``stop backing the filibuster that is protecting the current corrupt campaign financing system.''
the ads were purchased by common cause, the self-described citizens lobby that is the most active organization pushing congress to change the campaign laws
the senate is the main congressional battleground for campaign finance legislation. the house has passed such bills in the past, only to see them die in the senate
house democrats have drafted a campaign revision package for house races but are sitting on it until the senate approves legislation
soviet citizens will be allowed to take out large bank loans to build private homes under a government decree published sunday that marks a major change in tackling the tenacious housing problem
the decree published on the front page of the communist party daily pravda said the government hoped to ``activate the human factor'' and get soviets to build their own homes with the help of government loans
it also calls on large industrial enterprises to take up a bigger share of the burden in providing housing. it makes clear that small groups of soviets who want to produce building materials or work as carpenters in their spare time are encouraged to do so
one in five soviet families currently lives in what is referred to as communal housing, which can be anything from a bunk in a collective farm barracks to a couple of rooms in an urban apartment shared with another family
soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev has followed in the footsteps of his predecessors in promising a separate home or apartment for every family, vowing to eradicate the housing shortage by the year 2000
but progress in putting up new apartment buildings has been slow, much of the existing urban housing is in poor condition and construction quality remains the subject of frequent citizen complaints
statistics published last month on the nation's economic performance in 1987 claimed 13 million families had been given improved housing. but the yearly statistical reports do not indicate how many families are displaced by major renovation or demolition projects under way in many cities
the pravda decree announces that ``unjustified restrictions'' on housing construction and purchase of building materials have been removed, but did not say what the restrictions were
private construction in the past has been discouraged as the government attempted to cut down on pilferage of scarce building materials from state enterprises, and also to prevent individuals from building homes exceeding the unspoken limits of socialist austerity
two years ago, the ruling politburo issued an order broadening the availability of private gardening plots, but said the land should not be used for building huge ``dachas,'' or country homes
those regulations, which limited the gardening huts to cabin-size, may have been among those scrapped in the government's attempt to get homebuilding going wherever possible
state construction enterprises have endured a barrage of media criticism over the years for failing to turn around the chronic housing shortage that has troubled this nation since before the 1918 revolution. the state's slow pace in improving housing conditions likely encouraged party and government officials to revise the regulations that have held back private construction
the new decree orders officials to make building plots available and appears to especially encourage construction in rural areas
loans of up to 20,000 rubles _ about $33,000 at the official exchange rate _can be taken out by those living in rural regions and paid back over 50 years, pravda said. the money borrowed by city dwellers must be repaid within 25 years
under the previous regulations governing private construction, no more than $5,000 could be borrowed from state banks and had to be repaid within a decade
the amount of interest to be charged on the larger loans was not specified in the decree, but borrowing rates traditionally have been between 1 percent and 3 percent a year
monthly pay for a soviet industrial worker averages $330
a $30,000 polio immunization fund created in 1963 by the burlington county medical society has finally been spent, after one last round of donations
the last $1,000 recently was donated to a worldwide polio fund sponsored by rotary international, said dr. harold r. reeve, president of the medical society
reeve, a urologist, said the final donation was ``a fitting conclusion'' to the fund. ``there just wasn't enough to perpetuate it anymore,'' he said in an interview last week
before vaccines eradicated it in this country, polio was a deadly killer and crippler of children and young adults
when the first oral polio vaccine became available in burlington county in 1963, the medical society arranged a mass immunization on two sundays in december of that year at schools and churches
the charge, if people could afford it, was 25 cents. otherwise the vaccine was free
about 100,000 people were vaccinated and the effort raised about $70,000, with about $40,000 going to pay for expenses
the medical society decided the remaining $30,000 should be used for the benefit of the community, reeve said
over the years the fund paid for first-aid classes, blood banks, anti-smoking campaigns, a pollution study, physical fitness programs and other public health projects. it was there when a scabies outbreak closed one of the county hospitals and when county officials decided to open a county health department
by the beginning of 1988, the fund had dwindled
it was down to nothing,'' reeve said. ``i think a few people had to chip in just to bring it up to $1,000.''
he said the $1,000 donation will immunize 8,000 children against polio in third world countries
the people of this community had contributed to the welfare of this community and now it is helping the world community,'' reeve said
the difficult task of finding good and affordable child care is drawing attention from so many diverse groups this election year that a stronger federal role in the patchwork system appears inevitable
both liberals and conservatives are trumpeting the need to address what some call a national crisis, spurred by the soaring number of working mothers
and in the last two weeks, both the national association of manufacturers and the u.s. chamber of commerce have cautiously endorsed at least some form of federal involvement
the issue is certainly heating up,'' says helen blank, director of child care for the children's defense fund. ``we're seeing more tragedies, more evidence of the system being fragile because it's pushed too far. you push and you push and you push and finally you start to fall over the edge.''
the children's defense fund was the moving force behind a $2.5 billion child care bill scheduled for hearings thursday in the house and the following thursday in the senate. also under discussion is a $375 million proposal sponsored by republicans, who have scheduled a news conference for tuesday
the gulf between the two bills is wide, both in money and philosophy. but proponents of the more ambitious plan say they are heartened by the existence of the gop bill, particularly because its senate sponsor _ republican orrin hatch of utah _ is among the most conservative members of congress
we have a tremendous amount of focus on child care and a tremendous desire to do something. and when people want to do something, there's usually room for agreement,'' blank said
you always have an advantage in an election year,'' she added
the flurry of congressional activity follows several hearings featuring the testimony not only of experts in child care and child development but of people with first-hand exposure to the problem _ including a policewoman who found two children dead in a clothes dryer. their mother had tried and failed to find supervision for them before she left for work
the $2.5 billion ``act for better child care services,'' or abc bill, was introduced last year by sen. christopher dodd, d-conn., and championed by the 122-member alliance for better child care
the money would be used to help states subsidize child care for low- and moderate-income families, increase the number of child care facilities and staff, and coordinate child care resources. the bill also calls for federal health and safety standards for day care centers and homes, and training standards for day care workers
the hatch bill would give states $250 million for grants to local governments, businesses and others to improve child care services. the bill also would limit the liability of child care providers, help states set up liability insurance pools, help home providers make capital improvements and give tax credits to employers with on-site child care
the national association of manufacturers last week adopted a statement saying the federal government should ``encourage affordable, quality child care through a bottom up approach and use of incentives.'' the group said any legislation should allow flexibility, address the liability problem and ``be guided by fiscal realities.''
the chamber of commerce board of directors, in a statement approved feb. 10, also endorsed a federal role providing incentives and limiting liability. the government also should identify programs and disseminate information, the chamber said, while regulation should be carried out at the state or local level
all this points to a growing recognition that something has to be done,'' blank said of the hatch bill and the two business groups' statements. ``it just doesn't go far enough. ... we attack the issue in a more systematic fashion. the private sector just can't make day care on its own. we try to help the private sector by creating a logical system in which they can invest.''
blank declined to discuss what kind of compromise might be acceptable to the children's defense fund except that it must do more than the hatch bill
it would be awful if we had some small child care bill that didn't put us in the right direction,'' she said. ``it's very important for the sake of children ... for us to really be cautious and careful about what the federal government does after years of inattention to child care.'' image</head>
corn sugar and artificial sweeteners are gaining a bigger share of the market, so the cane and beet sugar industry plans to fight back with a $4 million television advertising campaign
we'll associate sugar with happy moments,'' said tony contreras, vice president of marketing for the sugar cane growers cooperative in belle glade. ``it's a very positive, lifestyle-type of campaign.''
following the lead of the beef, pork and poultry producers, the sugar industry will try to increase consumption by focusing on the ``sweet, pure and natural'' aspects of sugar. the campaign starts in march
ads will be paid for by florida's sugar cane growers and other u.s. cane and beet growers, refiners and processors
the sugar market has dropped since the early 1970s. actually the market drop was caused by corn sweeteners,'' said charlie shamel, president of the sugar association, a washington, d.c., trade association
manufacturers of soft drinks, canned fruit, table syrups and other processed foods have turned to less expensive corn sweeteners instead of cane or beet sugar
meanwhile, total sugar consumption also is down. per capita sugar use could decline to 35 to 40 pounds by 1995 if the trend continues, or less than half of what it was in the 1970s, shamel said
unlike its magazing advertising last year which took a an anti-aspartame tack, the sugar association tv drive will take a pro-sugar approach. the campaign is geared toward giving viewers ``permission to eat sugar,'' contreras said
we're not suggesting anyone pig out on sugar,'' said shamel. ``but used in moderation, it tastes good and has a lot of benefits: adds texture in cakes, flavor to bland foods.''
past advertising by the sugar industry has been criticized for its use of a u.s. food and drug administration task force report that the industry said confirms ``sugar is safe.''
the 1986 fda report found no direct link between sugar and major diseases, such as diabetes, hypertension, cancer, gallstones, glucose intolerances or hyperactivity in children
a washington, d.c., consumer group claims the sugar industry manipulated the fda report
the study was part of a series of studies on food additives,'' said bruce silverglade, legal affairs director for the center for science in the public interest. ``sugar was thrown in there along with artificial sweeteners. it did not focus on the role sugar plays in the diet.''
the american dental association maintains that while sugar may be a natural product, ``it causes tooth decay,'' said rick asa, spokesman in chicago for the ada, which favors sugar substitutes
the collected writings of the chinese communist party's purged co-founder, chen duxiu, have been published for the first time since 1922, an official report said sunday
the publication, announced by the state-run xinhua news agency, indicated that current party leaders are taking a more relaxed attitude toward people who clashed with mao tse-tung during the formative years of the chinese communist party
chen was the founder of the new youth magazine that radicalized many chinese students in the 1910s and 1920s. he also was a leader of the 1917 ``may fourth movement'' that opposed japanese expansionism and china's inability to fight it
he and beijing university librarian li dazhao are regarded by western scholars as the chinese communist party's founders. he became the first party general secretary in 1921, but was ousted in 1927 after the failure of the party's policy of cooperating with the non-communist nationalist party of chiang kai-shek
chen was strongly influenced by the soviet-led comintern, which argued that china needed a democratic revolution before it could proceed to a communist-style revolution
the comintern, dominated by soviet dictator josef v. stalin, argued that china's middle class, represented by chiang's nationalist party, would play a major role in the first revolution and therefore deserved the help of all good communists
chen supported that position and clashed with activists such as mao who believed that the party must split with the nationalists, establish its own roots among the workers and the peasants and work directly for a communist revolution
chen was purged from the party in 1929, partly at mao's instigation, and went down in chinese history books as a ``right opportunist,'' his role in the party's founding downplayed. he died in 1942
xinhua said the collection of 270 essays, letters and other writings by chen were republished by the people's publishing house in his native anhui province in central china. it said the collection first was published in shanghai in 1922
xinhua described the collection as ``invaluable to the study of modern chinese history and the history of the party in its early stage.''
during the last 12 years, chinese authorities have moved away from a blind allegiance to the ways and words of mao, going so far as to criticize his economic policies and blame him for the excesses of the cultural revolution
northern ireland's police chief charged sunday that british investigator mishandled an inquiry into allegations his force had a ``shoot-to-kill'' policy
john stalker was considered to be the most proficient detective investigator in the united kingdom,'' sir john hermon said of the former deputy chief constable of manchester, who investigated hermon's force
but he said, ``i believe there are many people who are more mature and more experienced who could have done it.''
hermon was speaking on a british broadcasting corp. northern ireland television program to be broadcast monday night. a partial transcript of the program was released sunday
stalker was sent to northern ireland to investigate the killing of six unarmed roman catholics by police in three incidents in late 1982
the british government announced jan. 25 that while evidence had been uncovered of a conspiracy to pervert the course of justice, it would not prosecute any northern ireland police officers implicated by stalker. it said prosecutions would hurt national security
the decision has put a strain on anglo-irish relations. ireland views the case as a test of britain's resolve to reform northern ireland's justice system and protested the decision not to prosecute
stalker has published a book alleging that his investigation was systematically obstructed by senior officers, including hermon. he claimed he was removed from the inquiry before he could complete it because his findings were likely to lead to murder charges against police officers
five of the shooting victims were acknowledged irish guerrillas fighting to drive the british out of northern ireland. the sixth was a roman catholic teen-ager with no connections to the guerrillas
their deaths in police ambushes led to allegations that anti-terrorist officers were operating a ``shoot-to-kill policy'' to wipe out guerrillas without having to go through normal judicial procedures
hermon distributed a statement to police officers throughout northern ireland last week accusing stalker of publishing ``untruths, distortions, and inaccuracies.''
stalker, who has retired from the force, said he stood by his book
just two months before the april 24 presidential election, the socialist party launched its campaign sunday under a large banner reading: ``mitterrand generation.''
the only problem: president francois mitterrand has yet to declare
still, mitterrand, who is a socialist, is widely expected to run for another seven-year term. the announcement will likely come in mid-march
the official beginning of the socialist campaign came before a crowd of about 2,500 people in this city in central france, in a region mitterrand once represented in parliament
lionel jospin, the party's first secretary, told the audience that france was involved in ``an extraordinary campaign which we are approaching in an unusual way, our candidate not being known, the president being socialist.''
the slogan ``mitterrand generation'' has already appeared on posters around france, which show a baby reaching up to the hand of an unseen man. party officials say the campaign could be adopted either by mitterrand as a candidate, or by his socialist successor if the president does not run
opinion polls show mitterrand in first place, with premier jacques chirac and former premier raymond barre, both conservatives, fighting for second place
the top two candidates in the april 24 voting will face off in a decisive second round may 8, unless one of them wins more than 50 percent of the vote in the first round
in a radio interview sunday, a leader of the union for french democracy, an alliance of parties supporting barre, said his side was ``campaigning against a phantom who is hiding behind the draperies at the elysee,'' the presidential palace
mr. mitterrand would like to be a candidate without putting his name on the ballot,'' said jean-claude gaudin, president of the union's parliamentary group. ``it's ideal for someone who does not have many things to say and does have many things to hide.''
other candidates include jean-marie le pen of the extreme right national front, andre lajoinie of the communists and pierre juquin, a dissident communist. all are running far behind mitterrand, barre and chirac
one paper seemed to have the answer sunday
mitterrand has made his decision,'' was the banner headline in the journal du dimanche newspaper. the story, however, said it did not know which decision the president had made. toulouse-latrec, in 2nd graf, subs for paris-dated second item.</note>
