authorities found a man's decomposed body at a house occupied by children and other relatives, some of whom claimed the deceased man was ``doing much better'' and would awaken after his dealings with god
i understand they were seeing a voodoo man,'' pickens county coroner herbert latham said of the deceased man and his relatives. he said the man had been dead about three weeks when the body was found
pickens county sheriff david abston identified the dead man as jessie james latham, 42, not related to the coroner. abston said latham recently returned to alabama from new york
l.c. keasler, director of the pickens county department of human resources, said agency workers went to the mobile home feb. 14, but were refused entrance. the agency workers returned wednesday with authorities and discovered the body
this was a weird case,'' the coroner said sunday. he said that when the body was located, the dead man's relatives ``tried to convince me that he was still alive, that god was dealing with him, that he was fine.''
the coroner said the body ``was just dried up.'' he said an autopsy was performed before the body was buried saturday at a local cemetery
the coroner said that although no foul play was suspected, he was awaiting hospital records from new york before announcing the cause of death. he said the deceased man was apparently aware he was suffering from a fatal disease and was seeking help
the county workers had gone to the home in the first place because an anonymous caller from new york had said he was sick and that someone should see that he was taking his medication
abston said that when latham returned to alabama from new york, he was picked up at the tuscaloosa airport by his sister, catherine latham, who took him to a motel in reform. the two stayed there for two weeks
dilip bhakta, the motel manager, said he never saw latham, but asked latham's sister to leave the motel feb. 2 ``because of the smell.''
she never would let anyone come in the room and would meet our maids at the door to get materials,'' bhakta said
bhakta said the odor from the room ``was very strong _ very offensive'' and that there were several complaints about it from other guests
ms. latham said she took her brother on jan. 22 to a man in hale county who advised that he drink goat milk with some pills he gave him. she said she took her brother to the trailer residence on feb. 2
the nine occupants of the trailer included two infants and several teen-agers, the coroner said
ms. latham dismissed the claim that her brother was treated by a ``voodoo doctor.''
abston said the woman told him that her brother was alive when he was moved and did not die until the day authorities found his body in a bedroom of the trailer
he was pretty well decomposed at the time and the odor all around the trailer was pretty strong,'' the sheriff said. ``some of the kids playing in the yard were wearing face masks, like in an operating room.''
asked if there were any supernatural elements or voodoo involved in the treatment, ms. latham told the tuscaloosa news on saturday: ``i don't like to use that word. i'm not working for the devil _ i work for god
all i could do was minister to him. he's in god's hands now.''
