secretary of state george p. shultz and soviet foreign minister eduard a. shevardnadze claimed ``good progress'' sunday in daylong talks on arms control, human rights and regional conflicts
but a soviet foreign ministry spokesman sharply criticized the u.s. nuclear rebuilding program in western europe
the spokesman, gennady gerasimov, said the modernization program in nato countries clashed with the new u.s.-soviet treaty to scrap intermediate-range missiles
gerasimov said building new missiles with a range less than 315 miles was ``incompatible with the strengthening of european security.''
the u.s. state department spokesman, charles e. redman, dissociated the u.s. government from the soviet criticism
otherwise, both sides gave extremely upbeat appraisals of the shultz-shevardnadze talks, he said
they both agreed without any hesitation whatsoever that the atmosphere was excellent throughout the day, that they were businesslike, and they both agreed we made good progress across the range of issues,'' redman said
shultz took an hour off to meet with noted soviet dissident andrei d. sakharov, who wished him well in pressing for human rights reforms. shultz called the 1975 nobel peace prize winner ``an inspiration'' and a ``model and symbol'' to the world
they met in sakharov's seventh-floor apartment. sakharov said serious soviet reforms were under way but the country had not made enough progress yet on human rights or on afghanistan
he was sent into internal exile in gorky for almost seven years in 1980 for speaking out against the soviet military intervention in afghanistan
the treaty to ban u.s. and soviet missiles ranging from 315 to 3,125 miles was signed by president reagan and mikhail s. gorbachev at their summit meeting in december in washington. the treaty is now before the u.s. senate and the supreme soviet for approval
gerasimov said the soviets were eager to see the treaty placed in force and had begun withdrawing short-range missiles from east germany and czechoslovakia. but he rejected assertions by u.s. officials that the soviets were holding back on a date for the next summit meeting until the treaty was approved
we never stated directly that there is some sort of link,'' the soviet spokesman said
reagan and gorbachev agreed to meet in moscow but did not set a date. redman said the two sides were considering ``the general time frame of mid-may or early june.''
redman said holding a summit did not depend on completing another treaty to halve the superpowers' arsenals of long-range bombers, land-based missiles and submarines
negotiations in geneva have slowed down over ways to verify the cutbacks and over the u.s. program to develop an anti-missile defense in space
shultz discussed verification procedures with shevardnadze. a joint statement to be issued after talks monday with gorbachev. shevardnadze is expected to deal with the problem and also compliance with the 1972 anti-ballistic missile treaty, which the soviets say prohibits much of the u.s. ``star wars'' program
earlier, at the opening of the talks, shevardnadze staked out an active role for the soviet union in the u.s. drive to set up arab-israeli peace talks
shultz has questioned whether the soviets are eligible, given their record on human rights and lack of relations with israel
but shevardnadze said the soviets intended to be more of a factor
the issue of soviet participation is one of the key items on shultz's agenda during his talks in moscow
the soviets broke relations with israel after it defeated egypt, then a soviet ally, in the 1967 mideast war. however, a small group of soviet diplomats was sent to israel last year to take care of some consular matters
prime minister yitzhak shamir of israel has resisted soviet participation in the search for a middle east settlement. in addition to not having relations with israel, the soviets generally support arab positions
the official tass news agency issued a mostly favorable review of the first day of talks between shultz and shevardnadze, declaring that the officials sought ``first of all ways to utilize the potential'' created at the washington summit in december
shultz also pledged the united states would not give up the struggle for a better kremlin record on human rights, including emigration
we are never content until all these cases are resolved in the proper way. no matter how discouraging it may sometimes seem, we will never give up,'' the secretary said in brief remarks at the home of consulate chief max robinson
vera zieman, the 11-year-old daughter of a jewish couple that has been refused permission to emigrate for more than 10 years, gave shultz a photo of herself with him at a previous meeting and signed it, ``from a lifelong refusenik.''
on another subject, a senior u.s. official who spoke on condition of anonymity said shultz would seek soviet support for ``an early vote'' in the u.n. security council to impose an international weapons embargo against iran
the soviets joined with the united states last july in a resolution that called for a cease-fire in the iran-iraq war. but they have held back from enforcing the resolution with sanctions
andrei d. sakharov told u.s. secretary of state george p. shultz on sunday the soviet union has not made enough progress on human rights or afghanistan to host a human rights conference, but reforms are under way
shultz visited the physicist and 1975 nobel peace prize winner at his seventh-floor apartment on a busy moscow street to underscore the reagan administration's concern about the soviet human rights record
but sakharov, who spoke to reporters for about 10 minutes after the 55-minute meeting, said shultz also questioned him about arms control and soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev's reforms
the soviet union wants to host an international conference on human rights, but western countries are resisting the idea because of soviet violations of human rights
as a precondition for such a conference, i see the liberation of all prisoners of conscience, and the complete end of the war in afghanistan,'' said the 66-year-old sakharov, who spoke to reporters on the sidewalk outside his apartment building
sakharov helped develop the soviet hydrogen bomb in the 1950s but increasingly turned his attention to human rights activities in the 1960s and 1970s. he won the nobel prize for that work, but was exiled to the closed city of gorky in january 1980 for speaking out against the soviet military intervention in afghanistan in december 1979
gorbachev said feb. 8 that the soviet union could begin withdrawing its soldiers from afghanistan on may 15 if u.n.-sponsored peace talks in geneva are successful
sakharov, dressed in a parka and fur hat, told reporters that his first meeting with shultz was a ``great honor'' and provided him with valuable information. he excused himself after a short statement, saying he had just recovered from the flu and could not stay outdoors longer
shultz visited the apartment with assistant secretary of state rozanne l. ridgway, chief arms negotiator max kampelman, u.s. ambassador jack matlock and state department spokesman charles e. redman
a u.s. official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said sakharov's wife, yelena bonner, served tea to the group in sakharov's living room. matlock served as translator, the official said
asked by reporters about the meeting as he stepped into his car, shultz said it was an ``inspiration.'' he then left for talks with soviet foreign minister eduard a. shevardnadze, whom he met earlier in the day
sakharov said shultz asked him what the soviet union must do to comply with the 1975 helsinki agreement's provisions on human rights. sakharov said it was ``very important'' for the soviet union to change legislation ``which makes punishment for one's convictions possible.''
on arms control, sakharov said he reminded shultz that he stood for ``maximum restraint'' on the u.s. strategic defense initiative, or ``star wars'' program for a space-based shield against nuclear attack
that issue is a stumbling block in talks that may lead to an agreement to halve their arsensals of long-range nuclear weapons
he said he valued ``very highly'' the treaty eliminating medium-and shorter-range nuclear missiles that gorbachev and reagan signed in washington dec. 8
sakharov told shultz the gorbachev's effort to restructure soviet society is a ``deep phenomenon'' and ``very serious,'' he said
sakharov has been less active in the dissident movement since returning from exile in december 1986, but occasionally speaks out on issues such as human rights, nuclear power and more openness in soviet history. he has returned to his work in the soviet academy of sciences. cairo, scheduled meetings, details. pickup 4th pvs: `dudin said ...'</note>
a senior u.n. official said sunday that palestinian unrest in the occupied west bank and gaza strip has created a new urgency for arab-israeli peace efforts
what has been going on in the occupied territories has created a new situation,'' said u.n. undersecretary-general marrack goulding, who arrived in cairo on the last leg of a regional tour
he told reporters in amman, jordan, earlier sunday that the protests, which began dec. 8, underlined ``the pressing need for progress towards an in-depth negiation for a just and lasting settlement
and i think it has brought home to all concerned that everyone has got to make a major effort,'' he added
goulding's two-day visit in egypt is his last stop on a tour that took him to tunisia, lebanon, syria and jordan. he visited israel last month
the u.n. envoy was scheduled to meet with foreign minister esmat abdel-meguid for talks on regional developments, egypt's state-run middle east news agency said
the official jordanian news agency said that marwan dudin, acting foreign minister of the occupied territories, told goulding in amman earlier in the day that israeli forces had killed 108 palestinians in the unrest, far more than the 61 deaths reported by the united nations
dudin said israeli forces had injured more than 3,000 arabs
mr. dudin gave me a list of names and ages, locations and dates, which i haven't had a chance to look at yet,'' goulding said. ``but we won't be carrying out a u.n. investigation as such.''
dudin's ministry is in charge of jordanian affairs in the west bank and gaza strip, which israel captured from egypt and jordan in the 1967 middle east war
most of the estimated 900,000 arabs on the west bank and some of the 600,000 in the gaza strip are citizens of jordan
goulding's visit comes a few days before u.s. secretary of state george p. shultz is scheduled to arrive in israel. shultz is expected to discuss recent u.s. suggestions to grant limited self-government to palestinians in the occupied territories as a step toward a final arab-israeli peace settlement
in some places, i encountered a sense of satisfaction that the united states is becoming active again on this issue, and there is obviously great interest in what secretary shultz is going to say,'' goulding said
but he added, ``i cannot claim to have encountered a great deal of optimism.''
