the cbs affiliate in the washington area, wusa-tv, mistakenly began its ``face the nation'' broadcast sunday with last week's preview of the new hampshire primary
commentator lesley stahl started the show with, ``welcome to `face the nation,' this is lesley stahl in new hampshire,'' and spoke of what would happen in last tuesday's primary
the error was not detected until more than five minutes into the show
at that point, republican presidential candidate pat robertson was talking about prophecies concerning the ``forces of evil'' in the world and an embattled israel. the tape was abruptly cut, and the show picked up with ms. stahl in mid-sentence asking israeli defense minister yitzhak rabin about israeli forces being out of control in the west bank
diane digit, wusa publicity manager, said as soon as engineers realized they were mistakenly running last week's show, they switched to a tape containing the correct broadcast
cbs affiliate stations around the country tape the weekly show from a feed transmitted by the network's new york office, she said
roadblocks used to bar florida fruit because of a feared citrus canker outbreak probably will be maintained to discourage shipments, despite a threatened lawsuit, a texas official said sunday
at this stage of the game, florida hasn't attempted to send any citrus fruit in by any of the roadblocks we've got out there and we don't anticipate that they will,'' said mike moeller, deputy texas agriculture commissioner
a roadblock on interstate 10 near orange, texas, was closed sunday because of the lack of activity
the state declared a 30-day emergency quarantine on florida citrus after the u.s. department of agriculture lifted a ban that was leveled following a 1984 citrus canker outbreak in florida
texas citrus growers and agriculture officials barred the florida fruit from the state, saying the risk of canker, which causes defoliation and mars fruit, still existed. roadblocks were set up along i-10 and interstate 20, and officials vowed to destroy any florida fruit shipments
florida citrus growers, meanwhile, have threatened a federal lawsuit against the state
moeller said he expects action on the suit will be delayed until a hearing thursday in mcallen
at that time florida and the usda will have an opportunity to come in and attempt to document whether or not we've got a canker problem,'' he said. ``we don't anticipate that florida will attempt to run the blockade anytime before that hearing.''
a british school teacher has been kidnapped in northwestern pakistan, the british embassy said sunday
geoffrey langlands, in his 70s, was reported to have been kidnapped as he was driving to peshawar from the north wazirestan tribal area saturday
jeremy moody, press attache at the british embassy, confirmed that landlands had been kidnapped but had no details of the abduction
langlands is an old man and devoted his life to pakistan. i'm surprised he was kidnapped,'' moody said
he said the embassy was doing everything possible to find out what happened and secure his release
abductions are common in the tribal regions
langlands taught at razmak college in razmak and has been headmaster there since 1978. he has also taught at aitcheson college in lahore to the southeast
press reports said langlands' pakistani assistant, gul khajan, was also kidnapped, but was freed later
a pan american jet and a british caledonian aircraft, carrying a total of 222 people, nearly collided over the southeast coast of england on sunday, the british airline said
an air traffic controller was later suspended _ standard procedure according to the civil aviation authority, which said the incident is under investigation
it is the second near-collision in southern england in two weeks and the latest in a series of incidents this year that have raised concern about safety among the controllers
british caledonian said its ba 1-11, carrying 70 people, was about 25 minutes out of london's gatwick airport bound for amsterdam when its pilot saw the pan am boeing 727 on ``a converging course'' just below and slightly less than one mile away, near southend, essex at 9 a.m
the american airliner with 152 people aboard was headed for london's heathrow airport from oslo, norway
as far as the b-cal captain is concerned, he did not have to make any alteration to course and had the other plane in sight at all times,'' said a british airline spokesman, unidentified in keeping with british practice
he noticed that although there was a potential conflict, the pan-am aircraft changed its heading,'' the spokesman said
press association, the british domestic news agency, said the american plane altered its course on instructions from air traffic control after a potential disaster was realized
british caledonian said its pilot filed an ``air miss'' report and that the pan am pilot was also filing a report
aviation authority officials said they did not know exactly how far apart the two planes were
aircraft are supposed to be three miles apart horizontally and 1,000 feet vertically
one air traffic official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said it appeared the incident happened when one of the two planes descended below its cleared altitude
we are not sure at this stage which one,'' the official said
an aviation authority spokesman, speaking anonymously in keeping with british practice, said: ``our preliminary findings indicate that it was not a serious air miss, but it's difficult to say what the separation was at the moment.''
he said controllers were suspended until an investigation has ``ruled out any gross error by air traffic control.''
two weeks ago a british airways lockheed l1011 and a balkan bulgarian tu-54 with a total of about 500 people on board were involved in a near-collision over the kent coast
two air traffic controllers were suspended and transport secretary paul channon ordered a special inquiry into the circumstances of that incident
israeli foreign minister shimon peres acknowledged sunday that he wrote to attorney general edwin meese iii in 1985 about a proposed iraqi pipeline, but said the note only indicated that he wanted to discuss the matter with secretary of state george shultz
peres, who was israel's prime minister at the time, previously has denied writing to meese that he supported the $1 billion, 540-mile pipeline project, which was never built
appearing sunday on abc-tv's ``this week with david brinkley,'' peres said he had sent meese a handwritten note regarding the project during the summer of 1985
i was told about the idea of laying a pipeline from iraq through jordan up to elat, which will add, in my judgment, more security to the whole region and that israel could have enjoyed oil for a lesser price,'' peres said
once i was told, i wrote to meese and i said that if this is the case, i would like to meet secretary shultz, a man for whom i have the highest regard, in order to discuss it and talk it over. that was the content of my letter,'' he said
peres has said meese sent him a handwritten letter in which the attorney general directed him to deal with then-national security adviser robert mcfarlane instead of shultz
the los angeles times reported earlier this month that meese told peres to bypass shultz because of a potential conflict of interest. shultz used to be an executive with bechtel corp., the huge san francisco construction firm which had submitted a bid to build the pipeline
independent counsel james mckay, who is conducting a criminal probe of meese, is investigating the attorney general's role in the pipeline project
meese has said his involvement in the project was ``entirely lawful, proper and responsible.''
at issue in particular is a 1985 memo sent by attorney e. robert wallach to meese describing the proposed project and mentioning planned payoffs to the government of israel and peres' labor party to ensure that israel would not attack the pipeline
wallach, a longtime friend of meese, had been hired by swiss businessman bruce rappaport, who had been enlisted by bechtel to help with the project due to his close ties to israeli government officials
federal law prohibits u.s. citizens from bribing foreign officials and states that the attorney general may take legal action to stop a violation if it appears that one is about to occur
rappaport has said he did not intend to pay bribes and that the payments would be standard business procedure and would come from profits from the pipeline or discounts on the oil
peres has denied repeatedly that anything of value was offered or accepted by him or his labor party in connection with the pipeline. he repeated that denial sunday
meese has said that he doesn't recall reading the portion of the memo mentioning payments, but said, ``i do not believe that it fairly implies that a violation of law was committed or contemplated in connection with the pipeline.'' apparently from world war ii. pulled up in boat's nets. no pickup</note>
a mine apparently left over from world war ii sank a french trawler in the english channel on sunday when it exploded in the boat's fishing nets, but all four crew members were rescued safely, officials said
an official at the cross-ma search and rescue headquarters in cherbourg, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the boat la minette hit the mine early sunday morning about 30 miles north of the normandy coast
a nearby trawler rescued the crew members and brought them back to port-a-bessin, their home port, 25 miles northwest of caen
another official at cross-ma said authorities believed the mine was one of many remaining after the june 6, 1944 allied assault on german defenses in normandy
the official, who also spoke on condition of anonymity, said fishing boats drag up world war ii-vintage mines or shells about once a month, but explosions are rare
president corazon aquino recalled sunday that when ferdinand marcos was preparing to go into exile, she reluctantly allowed him to stay overnight at u.s.-run clark air base
but mrs. aquino said on her weekly radio show that she had refused to let the ousted president go to his home province
mrs. aquino also said she had been told of the coup plot against marcos that led to the ``people power'' revolution feb. 22-25 1986 but she did not believe the planners would go through with it
mrs. aquino said sunday night that the role of the u.s. embassy during marcos' final hours as president was ``making arrangements for marcos to leave the country.''
marcos has claimed he was kidnapped by u.s. authorities and tricked into boarding a plane, thinking he would be flown to ilocos norte, his home province in the northern philippines
but mrs. aquino said u.s. ambassador stephen bosworth called her the evening of feb. 25 to say the marcoses would be flown to clark
after the marcoses reached the base, bosworth called her again and asked if they could stay overnight at the base and then fly to ilocos norte for a rest, she said
i said no, he can rest in clark, but he has to leave first thing in the morning. and so that was the agreement, and that was why marcos and his family flew the next day to honolulu,'' she said
