a brain-dead baby was taken off life-support machines after no recipients could be found for his organs, but another anencephalic baby remained on a respirator sunday, officials said
the boy known only as baby john, born tuesday and declared brain-dead thursday, had been kept alive in hopes that his organs could be transplanted in a pioneering program established by loma linda university medical center
the infant was removed from life-support saturday after doctors seeking a liver for four patients rejected his organ because it had deteriorated over a 36-hour period. no candidate with the same blood type was found for his heart, which stopped beating after he was removed from a respirator
the deterioration of the liver affected all the baby's organs, hospital spokeswoman anita rockwell said. ``when one organ begins to fail, the other organs begin to fail.''
baby john was the controversial program's first u.s. baby. another couple had hoped to enroll their child in the program, but the infant was stillborn on dec. 22
evelyn keys, born saturday with the same fatal birth defect in san antonio, texas, was flown to loma linda and placed in the transplant program for anencephalic infants _ babies born without most of their brain
baby evelyn is resting comfortably this morning. she shows some signs of brain stem deterioration but has not yet met all criteria of total brain death,'' ms. rockwell said sunday
anencephalic babies live only briefly. loma linda wants to establish a practice of sustaining such babies so the organs can be used for transplants after brain death occurs
baby evelyn, the first child of judy keys, 22, and airman todd keys, 21, stationed at lackland air force base, was born with only a brain stem
sustaining anencephalic infants for use as organ donors has raised an ethical debate, and loma linda is the first hospital in the united states to develop a medical protocol allowing the practice
under loma linda's guidelines, approved dec. 18, an anencephalic baby will remain on a respirator no longer than a week
if the baby is declared brain dead during that time, he or she becomes a potential donor. the rules require that two physicians not associated with the potential transplant recipient agree on a finding of brain death
after the week is up, the baby is removed from the respirator and allowed to die naturally, whether brain death has been declared by that time or not
several thousand anencephalic babies are born in the united states each year. their brain stems sustain basic functions such as breathing for a short time, but death occurs within hours or days of birth
ethical problems raised by the practice of sustaining anencephalic babies include the questions of whether such infants feel pain and whether it is ethical to prolong a life when it does not benefit that patient
last october, a brain-dead anencephalic girl was flown from canada to loma linda where her heart was successfully transplanted into the chest of newborn paul holc
the medical center, a seventh-day adventist hospital, has specialized in infant heart transplants. thirteen babies under the age of 4 months have received new hearts there. nine have survived
the center, 65 miles east of los angeles, became well known in 1984 when dr. leonard bailey unsuccessfully transplanted the heart of a baboon into an infant called baby fae
a woman convicted of involuntary manslaughter in the death of her baby on an airliner has been paroled after serving 120 days of a five-year sentence
julie killeen, 22, of san francisco pleaded guilty in october and was sentenced by platte county circuit judge john yeaman
yeaman placed ms. killeen on probation earlier this month, but declined to say why. california authorities will supervise her probation
ms. killeen's daughter was born june 30 in the lavatory of a miami-bound airliner during a 45-minute layover at kansas city international airport, authorities said. the baby died of suffocation
ms. killeen told police she dumped the baby's body in a trash can after the plane arrived at miami international airport so that her father wouldn't know she was pregnant. she also said she thought the baby was stillborn
a maintenance worker found the infant girl's body in the miami airport trash can. figures, supporters celebrating, rally canceled. pickup 10th graf pvs ``kyprianou, 55,...''</note>
a communist-backed millionaire narrowly defeated his veteran conservative opponent sunday to become president of cyprus in his first political campaign
i see this as a victory for cyprus,'' said george vassiliou, 56. during his campaign he promised that as head of the greek cypriot government he would push for reunification talks with the turkish side of the divided mediterranean island
vassiliou urged restraint by supporters, but isolated street brawls broke out between his backers and those of conservative glafcos clerides in nicosia, the capital
jubilant leftists set fire to clerides posters and banners, broke several shop windows and stoned cars outside a right-wing club
in unofficial final returns vassiliou garnered 51.63 percent of the vote and clerides 48.37 percent in the first closely contested election since independence from britain in 1960
clerides, 68, and vassiliou knocked out incumbent spyros kyprianou in a first round of balloting in the greek cypriot sector on feb. 14
vassiliou called off a pre-dawn election rally, telling the associated press: ``there is no victor or vanquished. we should all work together for the good of cyprus.''
he said he would make no immediate policy statements
clerides told state-run television: ``the cyprus people have chosen vassiliou as a new president. despite the small difference, there is no doubt he won the election.''
more than 90 percent of the 363,000 voters turned out to vote in the runoff. with 325,062 valid ballots counted from sunday's election, vassiliou had 167,834 and clerides 157,228.voting was compulsory for all those 21, and there were several thousand ballots ruled invalid
kyprianou, 55, had sought a third five-year term on a platform of no negotiations with the turkish side of the island unless 30,000 turkish troops and 65,000 turkish mainland settlers withdrew from the turkish-occupied north
rauf denktash, president of the turkish cypriot breakaway state established in northern cyprus in 1983, has offered to meet the new president in preliminary negotiations aimed at breaking the 3-year-old deadlock in peace talks sponsored by the united nations
cyprus has been divided since 1974, when the turkish army invaded the eastern mediterranean island following a short-lived coup by greek cypriot extremists favoring a union with greece
turkey seized the the northern third of the island and forced about 180,000 greek cypriots to flee to the south. turkish cypriots declared their own republic in 1983, but turkey is the only country to recognize it
the separation of the island has been the dominant issue in the election. clerides and vassiliou both said they would hold talks with the other side
clerides, a veteran negotiator who has held inconclusive talks with denktash in the past, promised to form an all-party national unity government to handle peace talks
vassiliou also stressed unity, but rejected the coalition proposal as unfeasible. he offered instead to appoint ministers of ``wide acceptance'' with no party affiliations
the new president will be sworn in next sunday
after the first-round defeat of kyprianou, the campaign developed into a direct left-right battle between vassiliou and clerides
clerides charged that vassiliou's independence was a sham, and that his election would result in communist domination
to bolster his national unity plank, clerides resigned as leader of the pro-western democratic rally party to run in the second round as an independent
vassiliou's camp charged clerides of being a ``right-wing, anti-labor reactionary.'' he was also accused of harboring fascist elements involved in the 1974 coup, which briefly overthrew the island's first president, the revered late archbishop makarios, and sparked the turkish invasion
the race was thrown open on thursday when kyprianou, the leader of the centrist democratic party, told the 91,000 people who voted for him, about 27.3 percent of the total, that they could choose either clerides or vassiliou
clerides topped the first round with 33.3 percent of the vote, followed by vassiliou with 30.1 percent
the turkish cypriot minority of 150,000, concentrated in the north, votes separately for the leadership of its breakaway state with its own constitution
if the u.s. congress approves new non-lethal aid for the contra rebels it will be ``erasing the word peace,'' president daniel ortega said sunday
in a two-hour speech at the opening session of the national assembly, ortega said the united states ``continues to propitiate and finance the war against nicaragua and despite the vote of congress against that aid, this chapter has not closed.''
he said president reagan will look for a way to obtain more financing for the contras by calling the assistance humanitarian aid
if the north american congress approves that type of financing, it would be erasing the word peace that it wrote when it voted against the funds, and would be putting (in) the word `war,' '' he said in the speech, broadcast over a government national radio network
that is the little game of congress, a congress where many interests, particularly egotistical, are involved and which is playing with life, hunger, security and the self-determination of the nicaraguan people,'' he said
reagan lost his bid in a house vote feb. 3 for a $36.2 million aid package that included about $3.6 million for weapons and ammunition, along with additional millions for military logistical support for the rebels fighting the leftist sandinista government
democrats prevailed in that vote, 219-211, after the party's leadership promised wavering members that there would be a later opportunity to vote on a package of contra aid that included only food, clothing, medicine and shelter
a group of democrats, together with one or two republicans who voted against the president's proposal, have been meeting to draft such an alternative
ortega claimed in his speech that the u.s. embassy in managua is financing opposition groups ``including the communist party.''
deputies from the communist party and two other opposition parties did not attend the assembly session
among the invited guests were uruguayan vice president enrique ernesto tarigo vasquez and the rev. roy bourgeois. the roman catholic priest was sentenced to 10 months in jail for trespassing during a demonstration at an air force base in florida where nicaraguan rebels reportedly were being trained
in the speech, ortega said 26,500 people have been killed since the war began in 1981 and 23,882 others wounded. other sources have said unofficially in the past that more than 40,000 have died
the war, he said, has cost the country $3.6 billion
in 1987 alone, he said, damage to the economy from the war totaled $376 million, more than the country's exports of $270 million
despite the war, he said, the economy expanded at an inflation-adjusted rate of 1.7 percent. it contracted 0.4 percent in 1986
ortega said consumer prices soared a whopping 1,347 percent last year, compared to 657 percent in 1986
the government recently unveiled a new program to try to control the runaway inflation rate, introducing a new cordoba currency, boosting prices of basic goods, increasing salaries and cracking down on speculators
ortega also praised the strategic weapons agreement between the united states and the soviet union
those agreements tell us that if understanding is possible at those levels, it may be easier for there to be understanding at other levels, and particularly in places where there are conflicts as in nicaragua,'' he said
two firefighters were suspended for allegedly manhandling and threatening a fire official because of the graduation of black and women rookies in the racially troubled fire department
the fire commission on saturday suspended anthony serpa, a 12-year veteran, for six days and walter glynn, an 18-year veteran, for four days, as part of a plea bargain. both will lose up to $1,500 in pay, officials said
the two, who allegedly were drunk at the time of the incident nov. 10, also will be dispatched to a different station daily for the next eight months as part of the agreement
