a drunken youth penetrated security devices designed to protect the royal family and was arrested about 200 yards from buckingham palace, scotland yard said early monday
the yard, headquarters of the metropolitan police, said the incident occurred sunday morning. it said no further action was planned against the youth, who was released after being cautioned for being drunk and disorderly
the yard declined to give the youth's name, address or age. it also would not detail how he got into the royal mews, which serves as stable and garage for queen elizabeth ii's 30 carriage horses, coaches and cars
he was arrested in the mews, about 200 yards from the palace
the mews is normally entered from buckingham palace road through a huge pair of doors set in a high wall topped with spikes, barbed wire, alarms and remote control cameras
the palace said the queen was not at buckingham palace at the time of the intrusion
she was at windsor castle, 21 miles west of london, where the royal family often prefers to spend weekends
security at 650-room buckingham palace and its 45 acres of grounds was improved after an unemployed drifter, michael fagan, climbed a drainpipe in 1982 to reach the queen's bedroom, sat on her bed and spoke to her before he was nabbed
a jury found fagan innocent of stealing a bottle of californian wine which he drank during a break-in at the palace earlier in 1982. he was never charged with breaking in to the palace because it was regarded as trespassing, a civil offense, and the palace wouldn't take him to court
