members of the ruling kenya african national union party test a controversial ballot-by-queueing system monday when, for the first time, they nominate candidates for general elections
under the new system, which the party introduced in 1986 to stop corruption and give members a bigger voice, they will nominate an estimated 750 candidates to contest march 21 general elections for parliament
thousands of other candidates are standing for seats on urban, rural and district councils
in previous elections, scheduled every five years, candidates were nominated by three people _ the party chairman, secretary-general and treasurer. president daniel arap moi also is president of kanu
by law, kenya is a one-party state and kanu must approve all candidates. some 4.3 million of the 20 million people are party members eligible to queue during monday's nominations
the secret ballot will be used at the general elections, in which all citizens aged over 18 years and registered to vote can take part. there are 5.5 million registered voters
some voters will not have the opportunity. candidates who win more than 70 percent of votes at monday's party nominations automatically go to the 200-member parliament
church leaders, lawyers and a few politicians have criticized the regulation and the new system, where voters must stand in a line behind their candidate
results of monday's nominations will be published at the end of february, when the party also is holding presidential nominations. but nobody is expected to challenge moi, who has ruled kenya for 10 years since the death of its first president, jomo kenyatta
the nation became independent from britain 25 years ago
