the high court will be asked tuesday to decide whether the clubs must admit women. members say they are havens of tradition; opponents say they are bastions of bigotry
for the old boys of the `old boys network,' it is time to wake up,'' said marcella maxwell, outgoing chairperson of the city's commission on human rights
official corruption linked to the drug trade is spreading around latin america, giving an anxious edge to longstanding predictions the illegal traffic could damage the region's political stability
because the people who produce and deal in cocaine, marijuana and heroin are so wealthy, the law enforcement agencies entrusted with the fight against them are often outmatched
indeed, bolivian president victor paz estenssoro estimates cocaine brings in $600 million each year to his nation, compared to $500 million for all legal imports combined
president corazon aquino, after weathering coup attempts and other political turmoil, begins her third year in office thursday more secure in power than at any time during her administration
but many who saw the feb. 22-25, 1986, uprising against president ferdinand marcos as the beginning of a new era in philippine politics are disappointed that dreams of social progress and reform remain unrealized
the coalition that propelled mrs. aquino to power _ reformist soldiers, human rights activists, the church and business groups _ has been shattered in the bickering that followed. pickup; also moved on general newswires</note>
the new owner of the new york post spent sunday talking with advisers about how to improve the prospects for survival of the nation's oldest continuously published daily newspaper, his spokesman said
one post employee called it ``the $22 million question'' _ whether multimillionaire businessman peter kalikow, aided by financial concessions by the post's unions, will be able to stem the tabloid's flow of red ink
equally intriguing was whether the real estate developer would tone down a sometimes sensationalistic style of journalism that has titillated, outraged, amused and generally entertained readers for more than a decade
kalikow will take over the post for $37.6 million on march 7, pending rank-and-file ratification of the concessions and verification by his accountants of the details
the sale of the paper by owner rupert murdoch cleared its final hurdle early saturday when leaders of the newspaper's 10 unions agreed to the $22 million in concessions to keep it alive. union members were expected to ratify the agreements this week
now kalikow has to do is figure out how to turn around one of the biggest money losers in the newspaper business
the post lost about $17 million before taxes last year, and about a quarter of its advertising in the last few months
its circulation has dropped from 700,000 to 500,000, partly because of a retrenchment in areas outside metropolitan new york
kalikow spent the day talking to advisers about ways to improve the post's prospects, according to howard j. rubenstein, his spokesman
the 45-year-old businessman, estimated to be worth about $500 million, has approved a $2 million promotional campaign for the newspaper and is scheduling luncheon meetings with leading advertisers and community and business leaders, rubenstein said. he also plans meetings with mayor edward i. koch and gov. mario cuomo to discuss his plans for the post
despite kalikow's many other business interests, ``he's going to be a very active owner,'' rubenstein said
under his contract with murdoch, kalikow promised to operate the paper for at least one year
rubenstein said kalikow was considering making the post strictly a morning paper, and denied that kalikow was leaning toward an afternoon-only paper with a smaller circulation and a higher price
despite its down-scale reputation, a $1 million marketing study commissioned by kalikow ``shows the paper already appeals to a fairly well-to-do audience,'' rubenstein said
kalikow is widely thought to want to back away from the paper's emphasis on stories of sex, crime and scandal. the post will remain a tabloid, but ``there will be a change in format,'' rubenstein said. ``there'll be changes in headlines, in the front page, in the emphasis of the paper.''
but, rubenstein added, the paper's new owner ``still wants it to be feisty and provocative.''
the specifics, he said, were being worked out by kalikow and frank devine, who is staying on as executive editor
the chairman of allegheny international inc. insists the consumer products company will continue business as usual even though it has filed for reorganization under federal bankruptcy laws
the pittsburgh-based company and some of its subsidiaries filed for chapter 11 reorganization in u.s. bankruptcy court on saturday
the company has total debts of around $845 million, while its assets are estimated at $735 million
i'm confident ai will emerge a stronger and more viable company,'' allegheny international chairman oliver s. travers said in a statement
included in the filing for reorganization and protection from creditors are allegheny international; sunbeam corp., its principal subsidiary; almet-lawnlite inc., sunbeam's subsidiary; sunbeam holdings inc.; and chemetron corp
allegheny international said a $175 million line of credit has been arranged through two major new york banks
the credit line, the company said, provides enough cash to run the companies during the reorganization
the reorganization will enable ai to operate with the stability needed to continue the successful growth of its consumer products operations and improve its complex capital structure,'' travers said
chapter 11 provides the means to implement corporate restructuring and continue the company's profitable turnaround,'' said travers, chairman since 1986
the action provides court authorization for the company to continue normal operations, he said. ``it's business as usual at our facilities.''
travers said allegheny international sought court protection because its complex capital structure and excessive debt could not be refinanced and reorganized without court protection
sunbeam and almet-lawlite are profitable, travers said, and wouldn't have had to file for protection if it weren't for allegheny international's complex financial situation
consumer products manufactured by sunbeam include small household appliances, electric blankets and barbecue grills. almet-lawnlite makes lawn and patio furniture
the bankruptcy filing does not affect sunbeam corp.'s consumer products operations in canada, mexico, venezuela and peru, according to the company. it also does not affect industrial and high-technology companies that allegheny international is in the process of divesting
since a change in allegheny international's management in august 1986, the company said it has sold 19 subsidiaries. the company said it also has reduced expenses and focused on its consumer products operations
last september, the securities and exchange commission charged the company with failing to record and to disclose perks given to former chairman robert j. buckley and other executives, including the use of company-owned residences and aircraft
allegheny international, prior to 1981, was known as allegheny ludlum industries. the company acquired sunbeam corp. that year for $534 million
when you're in charge of handling $7 billion in cash, sometimes a million or two can slip through the cracks, says ford motor co. money-manager malcolm s. macdonald
macdonald, assistant treasurer for the world's no. 2 automaker, says he flew into a panic once when $5 million couldn't be accounted for
the trouble began when he asked a bank to send $5 million to the central bank of brazil. the bank sent the money to the central bank of bolivia instead
there was a period of time when i was concerned about my career prospects,'' he said
keeping track of the growing nest egg of one of the nation's most profitable corporations can lead to a lot of anxiety, macdonald acknowledged
i wake up in the middle of the night sweating,'' he said
macdonald watches over more than $7 billion of ford's $10 billion-plus in cash and marketable securities
the money he watches is the money ford keeps on hand to pay its workers and its bills and to finance acquisitions. the rest of ford's liquid assets are handled by ford of europe
ford, which earned an automotive industry record $4.6 billion in 1987, entrusts more than 20 percent of its total assets to macdonald, who invests cash while making sure there's enough on hand to pay operating expenses
macdonald and his 26-person staff have to be careful how they invest the money, because the automaker must be able to get to it at all times
all our investments must be liquid. if mr. (bruce) blythe calls us up one day and says `i need $1 billion on march 30 to complete an acquisition,' we can't say `gee, that's going to be kind of tough. we bought these bonds, and we can't sell them yet,''' macdonald said
blythe directs ford's diversification planning
the guidelines that macdonald and his staff follow in investing ford's cash allow them to buy only high-grade securities and prohibit them from playing the stock market
on oct. 19 we were very grateful for that policy. there is plenty of risk in the car business without trying to get rich in the securities business,'' macdonald said
ford tries to keep less than $10 million in its bank accounts overnight because banks pay limited interest on corporate checking accounts, he said. the biggest chunk of ford's money goes into u.s. treasury bills and other government and corporate bonds. involved in `warfare.' inserts 3 grafs after 6th graf pvs, `there's going...', with further comment from spokesman, picking up 7th graf, `negotiations began...'; also moved on general newswires</note>
talks between pan am corp. and the 4,500-member union representing reservation clerks broke off sunday. the union vowed to disrupt operations through ``guerrilla warfare'' but put off any strike
pan am officials said airline service continued without interruption even if there eventually is a walkout, and threatened to discipline any workers disrupting service. but the federal mediator involved in the negotiations said he was optimistic the two sides would return to the bargaining table
we can strike any time we want,'' said william genoese, director of the teamsters airline division. ``we're going to pick our strategic time.''
asked when that might be, genoese said, ``today, tomorrow, next week, next month ... when it hurts them the most.'' the union had originally set a strike deadline for 12:01 a.m. sunday
genoese said reservation clerks and other teamsters members would attempt to disrupt pan am operations through ``guerrilla warfare,'' starting immediately
there's going to be trouble on the job,'' he said. ``they're not going to correct anybody's errors, they're not going to help anybody, they're not going to do anything for anybody. ... there's no more talks as far as we're concerned. we are at war with them, complete warfare.''
but a pan am spokesman, jeff kriendler, called genoese ``the jerk'' and his threat ``completely ridiculous.''
whereas the leadership may be at warfare with pan am, the rank and file are completely loyal to the company,'' kriendler said. ``it is not in their hearts to turn their backs on their customers.''
any workers taking part in that warfare would face ``discipline in the severest form,'' he added
negotiations began late saturday night at the request of a federal mediator, and continued for six hours past the midnight strike deadline. when talks broke off sunday morning, teamsters leaders said that union members _ reservation clerks, customer service agents and other clerical staff _ would continue to work
the talks resumed at 3 p.m. at pan am headquarters in manhattan, but recessed about a half-hour later when the company rejected the mediator's call for arbitration, according to genoese
the federal mediator involved in the negotiations, walter c. wallace, said after the talks broke off that he had asked both sides to re-evaluate their positions
the federal mediation board ``will stay in touch with the parties, and there will be a resumption of negotiations at an early and appropriate time,'' wallace said
i have been involved in negotiations where there have been shootings and bombings ... and i am still involved in negotiations'' with the antagonistic parties, he said
the labor dispute involves pan am's attempts to cut costs by $35 million through concessions by the teamsters. the ailing airline needs labor concessions totaling $540 million over the next three years, company officials have said
asked about the major points of contention, pan am spokesman jeff kriendler said, ``let's say that the company long ago established a $35 million objective of achieving cost reductions. what is negotiable is how we reach the $35 million figure.''
the company does not view the amount itself as negotiable, kriendler said, but the union maintains that it is
the company has vowed to maintain operations with replacement workers in the event of a strike. the transport workers union voted friday not to support a teamsters' strike, and pilots, flight attendants and flight engineers were not expected to honor picket lines
the teamsters represent workers at airports in boston, detroit, chicago, seattle, san francisco, san diego, los angeles, honolulu, houston, washington, new york and the florida cities of tampa, orlando and miami. the vast majority of the workers are employed in new york and miami. spokesman; subs 9th graf pvs, `a proxy ...' to conform; also moved on general newswires</note>
the new management team at united press international will meet on monday with representatives of the wire service guild to discuss the change in leadership at the money-losing news service
dan carmichael, a negotiator and guild spokesman, said sunday that upi's new president, paul steinle, asked to meet with guild officials about the transfer of control to world news wire group inc
the union ``wants to see upi remain an integrated, quality, competitive general international news service,'' carmichael said sunday
following the meeting, dr. earl w. brian, 45, the chairman of wnw, and steinle plan to hold a news conference to discuss the transition
efforts to reach brian and steinle, who assumes direct operational control of upi, were unsuccessful sunday. telephone numbers for the two were not available. calls to the washington hotel where wnw spokesman dwight geduldig was staying were not immediately returned
mario vazquez rana, a mexican publisher who paid $41 million to acquire upi from chapter 11 proceedings in u.s. bankruptcy court in june, announced friday that he had sold control of the company's stock to the wnw
vazquez rana granted wnw ``irrevocable proxy'' to operate upi for at least 10 years ``in exchange for present and future financial considerations totaling more than $55 million,'' upi said in a statement
under the arrangement, vazquez rana gave up all management and financial obligation for upi
a proxy represents a transfer of voting power represented by the ownership shares, but not the shares themselves. no stock changed hands, geduldig said saturday
under an earlier agreement with the guild, vazquez rana cannot sell his interest in upi without first giving the union the right of first refusal
the proxy arrangement enables wnw to take control of upi without buying it, but brian said in an interview in sunday's new york times that he intends to acquire the news agency and will meet with the union to discuss how that might be done
brian, who also is chairman of financial news network, the 24-hour cable television service, was an unsuccessful bidder for upi in 1985 and waged a vigorous legal challenge to vazquez rana's efforts to acquire the company
brian, a former surgeon, was california's health and welfare secretary while president reagan was governor of the state. he created biotech capital corp., which changed its name last year to infotechnology inc
brian declined to commit himself to preserving upi as a general news service. union leaders have expressed concern it might be turned into a specialized service, concentrating, for example, on business news
i'm not going in with any commitment other than to turn this business around,'' brian told the times
he added that vazquez rana's statement that upi loses $1 million a month may prove to be a conservative estimate
